**Brief description:**

CS8509 is a warning you get when a switch expression doesn't have a pattern for certain enum values. You get the same warning when the enum value is named as when the value is unnamed (via a cast like `(EnumType)9`). 

This means that even when every named enum value has been handled you still get a warning. This encourages programmers to add a pattern that handles every case (often times this case simply throws an exception i.e. `_ => throw new ..`).

But that means that when you add a new named value to your enum you won't get a warning since it has already been handled (incorrectly) by the catch-all pattern.

My suggestion:

If instead you get a different warning depending on whether or not the unhandled enum value is named or unnamed, people could decide for themselves how they would like to approach this issue by enabling/disabling the appropriate warning.

**Languages applicable:**

C#, I'm not sure if VB has switch expressions.

**Code example that the analyzer should report:**

With this enum:

```cs
public enum Operation
{
    Plus,
    Minus,
    Multiply,
}
```

this code:

```cs
public static string OperationToString(Operation op)
{
    return op switch
    {
        Operation.Plus => "+",
        Operation.Minus => "-",
        // Note!: Operation.Multiply has not been handled by accident
    };
}
```

and this code:

```cs
public static string OperationToString(Operation op)
{
    return op switch
    {
        Operation.Plus => "+",
        Operation.Minus => "-",
        Operation.Multiply => "*",
        // Note!: Every named enum value has been handled
    };
}
```

should be reported with different warnings.

**Additional information:**

I expect neither warning to trigger when you add a catch-all pattern. This means that when you intend for your switch expression to handle every named value you would generally not add a catch-all pattern so that you get an alert on those switch expressions when you add a new named enum value.

I think the [Flags] attribute should cause *unnamed* enum values that can be created by using `bitwise or` on *named* enum values should also be considered named for the purposes of these warning.

## Background and Motivation
The proposal is to modify the runtime to support nullable primitives on attributes stored in Assemblies when the non-nullable primitives are currently supported on attributes stored in Assemblies.   

## Proposed API
The proposed API is that the runtime would be modified to support the retrieval of attributes that have nullable structs from compiled assemblies where the non-nullable version of the type is already allowed to be in attributes stored in Assemblies. Below is an example of a compatible nullable type.

```
public class SomeAttribute : Attribute 
{
     public SomeAttribute(int? number)
     {
           Number = number;
     }
     public int? Number { get; set; }
}
```

## Usage Examples
The below example is how this change would be used.
```
SomeAttribute MyAttribute =
            (SomeAttribute) Attribute.GetCustomAttribute(t, typeof (SomeAttribute));
int? number = MyAttribute.Number;
```

## Alternative Designs

We could use the `HasProperty` pattern in this case, but it can lead to code that does not resemble the rest of the .Net ecosystem when it comes to nullable structs. 

## Risks
This proposed change likely requires changes in the C# compiler to make it useful.

